}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 1-9.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Like }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IX, this ninth canto is both liminal, marking the boundary between two \softline
large areas, and filled with classical reference.  And it is the first entire canto devoted to the \softline
transition from one poetic zone to another since }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXXI.  This sort of self-conscious poetic \softline
behavior puts us on notice, from the very outset, that we need to pay particular attention here.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Its reference to Aurora, surprisingly enough, has made this passage among the most hotly \softline
debated of the poem.  In the 'orthodox' version of the classical myth, Aurora, goddess of the \softline
dawn, arose from her couch, where she slept with her aged husband, Tithonus, to rise in the sky \softline
on her chariot, announcing the coming of day.  A brief and incomplete summary of the debate \softline
yields the following (for a summary of the essential arguments over the passage and an attempt to \softline
restore Benvenuto da Imola's central and daring reading of it see Hollander ["'La concubina di \softline
Titone antico': }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IX.1," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Electronic Bulletin of the Dante Society of America}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (July \softline
2001)]: Moore (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , Third Series: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Miscellaneous Essays}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Oxford: Clarendon, 1968 \softline
(1903)]), pp. 74-85, essentially solved this problem almost a century ago, but in fact the early \softline
commentators (to whom Moore pays little attention) had already done so.  (Paul Spillenger \softline
["Canto IX," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's "Divine Comedy": Introductory Readings II: "Purgatorio"}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Tibor \softline
Wlassics (Charlottesville: Lectura Dantis, University of Virginia, 1993), pp. 128-41], who devotes \softline
all but two pages of his 'lectura' of this canto to the opening tercet, is a rare discussant to revisit \softline
the glosses of Jacopo della Lana and Benvenuto, only then to deny their applicability.)  Nearly all \softline
of them are quite sure that Dante has invented a second myth, one in which Tithonus is married to \softline
Aurora 1 (of the sun) but has a 'relationship' with Aurora 2 (of the moon).  The poetic facts are \softline
simple, according to Moore.  The time is between 8:30 and 9pm, the cold animal is the \softline
constellation Scorpio (and certainly not that belated other candidate, Pisces, arguments for which \softline
identification Moore competently dismantles), and thus the aurora we deal with is that of the \softline
moon.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For a review of these tormented verses and their tormentors (up to 1975) see Steno \softline
Vazzana ({\u8220\'93}Il Canto IX del }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ,{\u8221\'94} in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio: letture degli anni 1976-{\u8216\'91}79}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Silvio \softline
Zennaro, Casa di Dante in Roma [Roma: Bonacci, 1981]), pp. 180-85.  And for one of the most \softline
interesting discussions of their meaning see Ezio Raimondi ("Semantica del canto IX del \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," in his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  Metafora e storia: Studi su Dante e Petrarca}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Turin: Einaudi, 1970 (1968)]), \softline
pp. 95-98.  See also Gino Casagrande ("Il 'freddo animale' e la 'concubina' [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IX, 1-6]," \softline
in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Filologia e critica dantesca: Studi offerti a Aldo Vallone}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Florence: Olschki, 1989], pp. 141-59) and Alison Cornish (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Reading Dante's Stars}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [New Haven: Yale University Press, 2000], pp. \softline
68-77).  A late 14th-c. Italian MS of Virgil, written by Astolfino Marinoni at Pavia in 1393-94, \softline
states that Dante had cited }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IV.585 here: 'And now early Dawn, leaving her saffron bed of \softline
Tithonus....'   For this and other citations of Dante in early Renaissance commentaries to the Latin \softline
classics see Gian Carlo Alessio ("La }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Comed{\f3 \'58}a}{\plain \fs24 \f1  nel margine dei classici," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studi di filologia \softline
medievale offerti a D'Arco Silvio Avalle}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Milan: Ricciardi, 1996], pp. 3-25).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 7-9.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Much has been made of the phrase 'where we were' by the 'solar aurorans' in the \softline
hopes of counterposing the northern hemisphere (site of the solar Aurora at this hour in Italy) and \softline
the southern (where Dante and his companions are becoming sleepy).  However, Dante is \softline
probably not contrasting the two hemispheres but the glow in the night sky of purgatory that \softline
spreads above them and the darkness of their surroundings as night advances.  For a similar 
situation, consider }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  II.8, the phrase 'l{\f3 \'42} dov' i' era' (there where I was) by which Dante \softline
refers to his situation in the southern hemisphere looking at the stars from there.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab His figure of speech involves mixing metaphors, as the night is given feet, by which she \softline
measures her hours, and wings that do the same thing.  The meaning is that the time is between \softline
8:30 and 9:00 pm.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab In a gesture of some charm but little possible historical foundation Benvenuto (comm. to \softline
vv. 7-12) reads the passage as revelatory of Dante's studious burning, not only of the midnight oil, \softline
but even that of the pre-dawn hours: 'vir studiosus erat solitus vigilare per tres horas noctis et \softline
evigilare in aurora sicut nunc fecit.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 10-11.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's Adamic sleepiness, that is, the heaviness brought on by his physical being, \softline
is adumbrated by a later passage (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XI.43-44), in which Virgil comments upon the difficulties \softline
experienced by this living soul as he climbs the mountain in his flesh ('la carne d'Adamo').  But the \softline
theme is introduced in the first canto of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.10-12) where Dante's 'sleepiness' is \softline
associated with Adam's, according to Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: \softline
Princeton University Press, 1969]), p. 81n., resuscitating Filippo Villani's gloss on this passage (as \softline
well as many another in his commentary), which suggests a figural relationship between the fallen \softline
Adam, sent forth into his exile from the garden, and the sinful Dante.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 12.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The reader has possibly not remembered that Dante and Virgil are still in company: \softline
Sordello, Nino Visconti, and Currado Malaspina have not yet been left behind; thus the group still \softline
numbers five.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 13-15.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's dream, occurring some nine hours after he fell asleep, takes place in the \softline
pre-dawn moments in which the swallow sings sadly }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 perhaps}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (if we credit the mythographers, \softline
most certainly Ovid (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Metam}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VI.412-674) in memory of the rape of Philomel by her sister \softline
Procne's husband Tereus and her subsequent metamorphosis into a swallow (in Dante's version, \softline
where most others prefer the nightingale -- see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XVII.19-20, a passage that \softline
makes the swallow here necessarily Philomel).  Tereus, like Tithonus, has had sexual concourse \softline
with each of two sisters -- if we accept the notion that the opening passage of the poem posits a \softline
lunar aurora (see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.1-9).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For the many (and mainly Ovidian) myths referred to in this canto see Picone ("Canto IX," \softline
in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Turicensis: Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Georges G{\f2\u252\'fc}ntert and Michelangelo Picone \softline
[Florence: Cesati, 2001 (1999)]), pp. 121-22.  For a related topic, Dante's debt to Ovid and his \softline
Ovidian tactics in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno,}{\plain \fs24 \f1  see Leonard Barkan ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Taccia Ovidio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : Metamorphosis, Poetics, and \softline
Meaning in Dante's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," in his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The Gods Made Flesh: Metamorphosis and the Pursuit of \softline
Paganism}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [(New Haven: Yale University Press, 1986], pp. 137-70, 317-27).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Dante's insistence on identifying Procne with the nightingale and not Philomel seems \softline
surprising to a modern reader, who has learned the tale the way that he or she believes it is found \softline
in Ovid (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Metam}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VI.424-676).  However, consideration of Ovid's verses when he indicates the \softline
avian identities of the two metamorphosed sisters yields results that are less than clear (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Metam}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
VI.668-669): 'petit altera silvas, / altera tecta subit' (one heads for the woods, the other for the \softline
eaves).  Most of us are certain that the woody one is the nightingale, alias Philomela, and that the \softline
one who lives amidst our houses is the swallow, alias Procne.  Dante, along with some ancient \softline
writers, preferred to have Procne as the nightingale -- and Ovid's text hardly removes this 
possibility.  A later text in the poem (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XVII.19) makes it clear that Dante refers here to \softline
Philomel as the swallow, since there Procne is clearly referred to as the nightingale.  The \softline
commentary tradition is interesting, in that almost every commentator before Lombardi (1791) \softline
simply assumed that the swallow in this passage referred to Procne.  Lombardi (comm. to verse  \softline
15), paying attention to the passage in the seventeenth canto, is the first to see the nature of the \softline
problem: Dante's adhesion to the aberrant classical and post-classical tradition that reverses the \softline
more usual labels.  Bosco and Reggio (comm. to this passage) argue that, in addition to the \softline
possible confusions derivable from Ovid's passage, texts in Virgil (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Ecl}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VI.79; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Georg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.15; \softline
IV.511-515) also might have made a clear understanding on Dante's part problematic.  Still \softline
valuable is Moore's brief discussion of the problem (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , First Series: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Scripture and \softline
Classical Authors in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Oxford: Clarendon, 1969 (1896)]), pp. 209-10; and see Georg \softline
Rabuse ("Schwalbe und Nachtigall," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Deutsches Dante-Jahrbuch}{\plain \fs24 \f1  38 [1960], pp. 168-92).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 16-18.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The greater truth, indeed the prophetic power, of dreams that came near morning \softline
was something of a commonplace in Dante's time.  See the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVI.7.  Beginning \softline
with Torraca (comm. to this passage) twentieth-century commentators have reminded readers that \softline
in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (II.vii.13) Dante had adduced our awareness of our own immortality from the fact \softline
that our dreams foretold the future for us. \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 19.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The formulaic expression (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 mi parea}{\plain \fs24 \f1  + }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 vedere}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) is an earmark of Dante's description of \softline
seeing in dream (see also }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXIII.36; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XV.85-87; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXVII.97-98).  For the \softline
consistency in Dante's oneiric vocabulary, dating back to the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vita nuova}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , see Hollander ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Vita \softline
Nuova}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : Dante's Perceptions of Beatrice,"}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  92 [1974]), pp. 3-4.  For studies in \softline
English of the three purgatorial dreams see Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
[Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1969]), pp. 136-58; Cervigni (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's Poetry of Dreams}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
[Florence: Olschki, 1986], pp. 95-180);  Baranski ("Dante's Three Reflective Dreams," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Quaderni \softline
d'italianistica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  10 [1989], pp. 213-36).  See also Stefanini ("I tre sogni del }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : Struttura e \softline
allegoria," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in the Italian Renaissance: Essays in Memory of Arnolfo B. Ferruolo}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. \softline
G. P. Biasin, A. N. Mancini, and N. J. Perella [Naples: Societ{\f3 \'42} Editrice Napoletana, 1985], pp. \softline
43-66).  For a recent Italian discussion of the oneiric elements of this canto see Calenda \softline
("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , IX: le forme del sogno, i miti, il rito," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Rivista di Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  1 [2001], pp. 284-301).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 20-21.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The reality corresponding to the eagle outside the dream is, naturally, Saint Lucy \softline
(identified by Virgil in verse 55), who is bearing Dante higher up the mountain while he sleeps in \softline
her arms.  But does this eagle have a symbolic valence?  Some early commentators (the Ottimo \softline
the earliest) read the text strictly literally: the eagle is the bird of Jove (or, perhaps, Jove in the \softline
shape of an eagle).  However, beginning with Pietro di Dante the eagle is allegorized as divine \softline
grace, and then, by various commentators up to and including Giacalone (comm. to vv. 19-21), as \softline
one form of grace or another (e.g., prevenient, illuminating, etc.).  In the twentieth century there \softline
was a vogue for a quite different allegorical reading, the eagle as symbol of empire.  (To be sure, \softline
this is often, even usually, true in this highly political poem; in this context, however, it seems a \softline
forced reading.)  It would seem most likely that a literal reading is the best procedure here, \softline
following the Ottimo (comm. to vv. 19-24), and simply noting that this eagle is the one who flew \softline
off with Ganymede, as the context allows and encourages, i.e., Dante dreams that he was carried 
off by Jove.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 22-24.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   John of Serravalle (comm. to vv. 19-33), following Benvenuto, allegorizes the \softline
eagle as divine grace and then equates Dante and Ganymede, thus making Dante 'one who lived \softline
with the gods.'  Casini/Barbi (comm. to verse 24) suggest that Dante had in mind Virgil's phrase in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Georgics}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.24-25, 'deorum / concilia' (company of the gods) when he wrote 'al sommo consistoro'; \softline
whether he did or not, his meaning seems clear.  Within the dream there is a certain aura of \softline
violence and fear (implicit reference to the forcible rape of Ganymede by Jove as eagle -- see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aen}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . \softline
V.252-257) masking the happier nature of the event: Dante being carried aloft gently by Lucy, \softline
and indeed, in a still happier understanding, on the way to the Empyrean, where he will, for a \softline
while, share the company of the immortal blessed.  In Virgil's ekphrastic moment (this scene \softline
appears woven on a cloak as a prize in the funeral games in honor of Anchises) the youthful \softline
prince (son of Tros, king of Troy) was hunting on Mount Ida on the Troad (not to be confused \softline
with the mountain of the same name on Crete referred to in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XIV.98) and was snatched away \softline
from his companions while his dogs barked after him; Dante's version has a more heavenly \softline
perspective, and we see the scene from Dante/Ganymede's eyes, as though he were rising in a \softline
balloon and watching the shapes of Sordello, Nino, and Currado fall back beneath him (the later \softline
poet has had to omit those wonderful Virgilian dogs).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 25-27.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The protagonist's thought within his dream is striking.  Since, within the dream, \softline
Dante is 'thinking like Ganymede,' his thought refers to a place elevated from the normal, e.g., on \softline
this mountain near Troy.  (Some commentators want to keep the usual imperial valence of the \softline
eagle by associating this Mount Ida with Troy and thus empire; however, the point would rather \softline
seem to be that the place is elevated, not that it is Trojan.)  And thus Dante would be thinking that \softline
only such extraordinary, i.e., 'higher,'  mortals like Ganymede and Dante Alighieri are chosen by \softline
the gods for their delight.  And this thought, perfectly in accord with what we will find out on the \softline
first terrace of purgatory proper, associates Dante with the sin of Pride.  Once again, however, the \softline
'reality' tells a different story: the true God is not interested in Dante's curly locks, but in his \softline
Christian soul; and He will pluck Dante up from the mount of purgatory for reasons better than \softline
those that motivated Jove.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The issue of Jove's homosexual desire for Ganymede is mainly avoided in the \softline
commentaries.  It is, nonetheless, noteworthy that, of the many myths available to Dante that \softline
might have expressed the love of the gods for a particular mortal, he has chosen this one.  For the \softline
question of Dante's attitudes toward homosexuality see Hollander ({\u8220\'93}Dante{\u8217\'92}s Harmonious \softline
Homosexuals [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  16.7-90],{\u8221\'94} }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Electronic Bulletin of the Dante Society of America}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [June \softline
1996]).  Durling (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 The "Divine Comedy" of Dante Alighieri}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , Notes by R. M. Durling and Ronald \softline
Martinez [New York and Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1996]), pp. 559-60, on the basis of no \softline
known evidence, is of the opinion that Dante was of homosexual predisposition but had never \softline
acted on his desires.  While that is probably more than can be shown to be true, the question of \softline
Dante's rather 'unmedieval' view of homosexuality (see discussion in the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XV.13-21) \softline
has generally not been dealt with as openly as it ought to be.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 28-30.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The eagle's descent may have still another Virgilian provenance: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XII.247-250, as Tommaseo (comm. to these verses) was perhaps the first to suggest; he has been followed \softline
by a number of others.  In that scene an eagle, described as 'Jove's golden bird,' offers an omen 
(arranged by Turnus's sister, the nymph Juturna) when it dives from the sky to snatch a swan out \softline
of the water and carries it off as its prey.  (This much of the drama bodes ill for the Trojans, but \softline
they are heartened, unfortunately for them, in the final result, when the rest of the water fowl \softline
attack the eagle and it drops the swan.)  The language is pertinent: Jove's golden bird is attacking \softline
the 'litoreas... avis turbamque sonantem / agminis aligeri' (the fowl along the shore, the clamorous \softline
crowd in their wing{\f3 \'50}d band).  From among this }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 agmen aliger}{\plain \fs24 \f1  the eagle picks one.  For the pun \softline
available to Dante on his family name (Alighieri/}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 aliger}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ) see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVI.1-3.  It \softline
seems possible that here Dante is conflating the two Virgilian passages in which a Jovian eagle \softline
seizes its prey and enjoying the coincidence that, in the last of them, that prey is associated with \softline
his own name, since he, too, while dreaming, is being lifted skyward in the talons of Jove.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The fire alluded to here is the ring of fire that was believed to surround the closer-to-earth \softline
sphere of air, just before one might reach the moon.  That this is the 'tanto... del cielo acceso' (so \softline
much of the sky set afire) of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.79 was possibly first suggested by Lombardi (comm. to  \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.79-81).  Thereafter it became a commonplace in the commentaries.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 31-33.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Once again the negative version of events put forth in the dream has a better \softline
meaning.  It seemed that the eagle and Dante were consumed in the ring of fire high above the \softline
earth, while actually Dante and Lucia have risen to the gate of purgatory, as we shall shortly find \softline
out, and Dante is being awakened, not by the pain of death, but by the late-morning sun on his \softline
eyelids (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX.44).  If there is a further significance to this detail, it would seem to refer to \softline
Dante's eventual arrival at the true 'sphere of fire,' the Empyrean.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 34-42.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The poet describes the narrator's awakening in terms that recall Statius's text \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Achilleid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.247-250), describing the stratagem employed by Thetis, Achilles' mother, in order to \softline
keep him from being 'drafted' into the Trojan war.  Taking him from the care of his tutor, the \softline
centaur Chiron (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XII.71), Thetis carries him in her arms, sleeping, to the island of Scyros.  \softline
Again Dante adverts to a mythic narrative that has a tragic result; Thetis's benevolent caution will \softline
not prevent the coming of Ulysses and Diomedes to Scyros and the eventual death of Achilles in \softline
the war.  Dante's 'comic' reality counters the Statian tragedy: Achilles is carried down from his \softline
mountain homeland to an island from which he will go off to his death; Dante is carried up a \softline
mountain situated on an island toward his eventual homeland and eternal life.  Rarely in the \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Commedia}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is the contrast between classical and Christian views, between tragedy and comedy, \softline
more present than in these classicizing passages that open this canto.  It is also true that the \softline
protagonist, as he experiences these new things, behaves very much as the 'old' man that he still is, \softline
and assumes that terror is a valid response to these miraculous events that, the reader can see, \softline
