}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 43-45.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante and Virgil have left their companions behind, down the mountain's slope, \softline
and are facing the east, the sun in their faces as the morning advances.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 52-63.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   As though to remind the reader that all the material relating to Dante's dream did \softline
have a counterpart in reality, Virgil's explanation 'glosses' the dream as it explains the coming of \softline
Lucy, while Dante slept, at the solar aurora, nine hours after he had seen the lunar aurora.  \softline
Sometime after dawn she began her ascent with Dante in her arms, leaving their companions in \softline
ante-purgatory.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \ul0 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 55.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   St. Lucy remains one of the more problematic presences in Dante's poem.  Exactly \softline
who is she and why is she so important to him?  Most commentators take her to be the early-fourth-century martyr from Syracuse, killed while Diocletian was emperor ca. A.D. 304.  She is \softline
usually associated with the well-being of the eyes, and this may have had some resonance for \softline
Dante who, in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  III.ix.15, reports a severe bout of eye trouble in the same year that he \softline
was composing his ode 'Amor che ne la mente mi ragiona.'  For whatever reason (and we shall \softline
probably never know it), Dante was obviously particularly devoted to the cult of this saint.  She \softline
has a presence in three major scenes in the work, the 'prologue in heaven' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.97-108), the \softline
transport of Dante while he sleeps in this canto, and the prospect of the inhabitants of the \softline
'stadium-rose' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXII.137).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Moore (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , Fourth Series: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Textual Criticism of the "Convivio" and \softline
Miscellaneous Essays}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Oxford: Clarendon, 1968 (1917)]), pp. 235-55, addresses the problem of \softline
an allegorical understanding of Lucy.  Does she represent 'illuminating grace'? 'cooperating grace'?  \softline
Gradually Moore undermines both these allegorical formulations and moves toward the notion of \softline
Lucy as Dante's 'patron saint' (p. 241), offering in evidence the phrase 'il tuo fedele' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.98) \softline
that reappears variously (Dante as Beatrice's 'fedele' in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXI.134; Bernard as Mary's \softline
