to another person }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 as such}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , and not as a symbol or type' (p. 243).  It was important that a reader \softline
like Moore, who still believed in the allegorical formulations that equated Virgil with Human \softline
Reason and Beatrice with Revelation or the Church (or, as Moore adds [p. 243], 'or whatever it \softline
be'), finds himself wanting to be rid of the rather fanciful associations that had previously been \softline
forced upon St. Lucy.  More recently Jacoff and Stephany (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Americana: "Inferno" \softline
II}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 1989]), pp. 29-38, crediting Pasquazi ("Il canto \softline
II dell'}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno: letture degli anni 1973-{\u8216\'91}76}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Silvio Zennaro, Casa di Dante in \softline
Roma [Roma: Bonacci, 1977 (1974)]), pp. 35-65) for his important contribution before them, try \softline
