Saint Lucy.  See also Anthony Cassell ("Santa Lucia as Patroness of Sight: Hagiography, \softline
Iconography, and Dante," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  109 [1991], pp. 71-88).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Little sense has been made out of the fact that in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  III.v.10-18 Dante invents two \softline
imaginary cities, which he designates Maria and Lucia, situated at the north and south poles \softline
respectively.  Is it significant that Lucy appears here, at the south pole, where, in the previous \softline
work, there stands an imaginary city bearing her name?  For recognition of the problem \softline
represented by those two cities, without attempts at a solution, see Poletto (comm. to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . II.97-99 -- and Poletto seems to have been the only commentator, at least among the seventy currently \softline
gathered in the DDP, to mention this intriguing passage), Jacoff and Stephany (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis \softline
