now see Cornish (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Reading Dante's Stars}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [New Haven: Yale University Press, 2000]), pp. 73-75.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 63.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Dante's line, 'poi ella e 'l sonno ad una se n'andaro' (then she and sleep, as one, \softline
departed) reminded Vellutello (comm. to vv. 64-69) of the end of the dream in Cicero's }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Somnium \softline
Scipionis}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (VI.29): 'Ille discessit, Ego somnio solutus sum' (He departed, and I was released from \softline
sleep).  Gabriele (comm. to this verse) had earlier signalled this resonance, and added also that of \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VIII.67, 'nox Aenean somnusque reliquit' (night and sleep both left Aeneas), a passage \softline
also cited by his student, Bernardino Daniello, discussing this verse.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 64-67.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   A final simile prepares us for the entrance to purgatory proper, comparing Dante \softline
to one who moves from dubiety to confidence, a movement that required that he reinterpret the \softline
dream and his associations in a positive light.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 70-72.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   At almost the precise midpoint of the canto Dante situates his second address to \softline
the reader of this}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  cantica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VIII.19-21 for the first).  It has caused two major \softline
interpretive problems, twice dividing its readers into two basic groups.  First, there are those who \softline
believe that it speaks of an increase of quality in the artistry employed by the poet, while others \softline
contend that it speaks rather of an increase of quantity.  This dispute is most readily understood \softline
by referring to translations of the poem; those in the first group have Dante say that he will \softline
employ better art; those in the second, more of it.  The early commentators, here represented by \softline
Benvenuto, think of the more elevated matter of purgatory needing to be supported by 'fictionibus \softline
magis artificiosis et sententiosis' (more elaborately worked and more highly signifying fictions).  \softline
Or, in another formulation, the art to describe the higher mystery represented by the portal of \softline
purgatory proper needs to be more artful (in this case allegorical) than at other times, but not \softline
necessarily more beautiful, the eventual Romantic view, yet one that is found even in John of \softline
Serravalle (comm. to these verses), who argues that the poem must from here on be more \softline
beautiful.  Costa (comm. to verse 71) continues Benvenuto's spirit: the reader should not be \softline
surprised, in his opinion, that, as Dante says, 'io cerco di sostenere con pi{\f3 \'6a} artificiose parole la \softline
materia sublime di che favello' (I seek to reinforce the sublime matter of which I speak with more \softline
elaborately worked words).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab A second question remains: does this heightening reflect just the scene that follows (as in \softline
the opinion of a minority, all responding to these verses, e.g., Tozer; Momigliano; Porena; \softline
Sapegno, who has a foot in both camps; Mattalia, or so it would seem; Giacalone; while Bosco \softline
insists that the phrase refers to both 'arty' halves of the canto), or all of the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  that is to \softline
come?  For the latter opinion see Francesco da Buti (comm. to vv. 64-72), who argues that, since \softline
the subject is now penitence, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 that}{\plain \fs24 \f1  is the higher matter that requires more art; in one form or \softline
another, this is the position taken by most commentators.  In the opinion of this writer, the \softline
address to the reader refers to the description of the gate, its warder, and the three steps in the rite \softline
of confession, all of which need to be understood in the tradition of the allegory of the poets, as \softline
we shall see.  It regards, in other words, matter both local and temporary.  In a similar vein see \softline
Vazzana ({\u8220\'93}Il Canto IX del }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ,{\u8221\'94} in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio: letture degli anni 1976-{\u8216\'91}79}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , ed. Silvio \softline
Zennaro, Casa di Dante in Roma [Roma: Bonacci, 1981]), pp. 177-80, arguing that what is at \softline
stake is the allegorical nature of what immediately follows.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 80.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The angel is seated not }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 upon}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (as some translate) the highest step but }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 above}{\plain \fs24 \f1  it, as will \softline
become clear from verse 104, where we learn that he is seated on the threshold of the gate with \softline
his feet upon the third step.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 81.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Beginning with Scartazzini/Vandelli (comm. to vv. 79-84), commentators resort to \softline
the Bible (Matthew 28:3) for the stern brightness of the angelic countenance: 'Erat autem aspectus \softline
ejus sicut fulgur' (His countenance was as the lightning).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 82.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The warder's sword is 'the sign of one who has authority to pronounce sentence,' in \softline
the words of Singleton (comm. to this verse), citing Benvenuto da Imola.  Singleton goes on to 
add that it is also 'reminiscent of the Cherubim with the flaming sword that were placed to guard \softline
Eden after Adam and Eve were driven forth.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 85.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The warder's words of challenge, 'Dite costinci' (Say it from there) repeat, as many \softline
note, the challenge of one of the centaurs to the approach of Virgil and Dante (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XII.63) and, \softline
like that one, probably reflect Charon's similar words (fare age... iam istinc [tell me... right where \softline
you are]) to the invading Aeneas in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  VI.389, as Daniello (comm. to vv. 85-87) was perhaps \softline
the first to note.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 86-93.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This scene represents an epitomizing replay of Virgil's and Dante's encounter with \softline
the guardian of all purgatory, Cato (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.40-93): challenge by the guarding presence, who \softline
wants to know if some higher authority permits this visit; Virgil's response indicating a female \softline
who had sent these 'pilgrims' on their journey (this time with no attempt to flatter the warder); the \softline
warder's courteous acceptance of the aspirants' desire to enter a sacred precinct.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 94-102.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The allegory of the three steps should be less difficult than it has proven to be.  \softline
Considering this problem, Carroll (comm. to these verses) cites Milton, describing the gate of \softline
heaven (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradise Lost}{\plain \fs24 \f1  III.516): 'Each stair mysteriously was meant.'  But what exactly does each \softline
of Dante's steps 'mean'?  Catholic doctrine, as variously expressed, presents the path to absolution \softline
from sin as running, in the Sacrament of Penance, from }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 contrition}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (the recognition and heartfelt \softline
rejection of a sin) to }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 confession}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (of the sin, voiced to a priest), to }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 satisfaction}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (in the promise to \softline
perform an act of penance as ordered by that priest, thus showing the genuineness of the \softline
confession).  This is the psychologically correct order as well as the one given by 'Scholastic and \softline
other Church writers uniformly' (Moore [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , Second Series: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Miscellaneous Essays}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
(Oxford: Clarendon, 1968 [1899]), p. 47), i.e., one is contrite, confesses, and then performs acts \softline
that will lead to }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 absolution}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , in the culmination of the sacrament.  Dante's first commentators are, \softline
however, more or less evenly divided as to whether the three steps found here represent, in \softline
sequence, (1) contrition, (2) confession, (3) satisfaction (this group is saving Dante from himself, \softline
as it were, i.e., they record what he }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 should}{\plain \fs24 \f1  have said) or (1) confession, (2) contrition, (3) \softline
satisfaction.  Holding for the first order see the Ottimo (comm. to vv. 94-95), Benvenuto (comm. \softline
to vv. 94-99), Anonimo Fiorentino (comm. to vv. 94-96), Serravalle (comm. to vv. 106-108); (2): \softline
Lana (comm. to vv. 76-77), Pietro (Pietro1, comm. to verse 76), Buti (comm. to vv. 94-105), \softline
Andreoli (comm. to verse 94).  However, it is fairly clear from the text that Dante has reinvented \softline
the order to suit his own purpose, beginning with confession and only then proceeding to \softline
contrition.  That this is almost certainly true is confirmed by a later text, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXXI.31-90, \softline
which offers a carefully orchestrated presentation of Dante's own penance before Beatrice, with \softline
the steps of that paralleling the steps found here, namely, confession, contrition, satisfaction, in \softline
that order.  Moore also points out that Dante's presentation of the third stage, satisfaction, is \softline
unorthodox, since he represents it as the love that came from Christ's self-sacrifice.  Thus, in \softline
Dante's scheme, the sinner first confesses his sin, then feels true contrition for it, and then moves \softline
beyond it in his imitation of and love for Christ.  Why he should have wanted to repackage the \softline
elements of what was a standard body of doctrine and belief is not a subject that has received \softline
adequate attention.  But we should not be surprised to find that this poet remakes any text or any \softline
doctrine to his own liking and for his own reasons.  The one element that does run through \softline
Dante's version of this sacrament is that its priestly element is curtailed in favor of inward 
recognition and performance on the part of the sinner, i.e., confession in Dante seems more a \softline
private form of self-recognition than is generally the case, contrition contains mainly internal \softline
elements (if it must eventually be given voice), and satisfaction seems more attitudinal than \softline
performative.  It also seems that Dante has moved elements of satisfaction into the second stage \softline
of the process, contrition.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Pietro di Dante (Pietro1, comm. to verse 130) is alone in referring to Psalm 99:4: 'Introite \softline
portas eius in confessione' (100:4, Enter his gates confessing your trust), as reflecting the situation \softline
here in the poem.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Some years ago Gregory Curfman (Princeton '68) suggested that the 'narrative' told by the \softline
three steps offered an epitome of the history of the human race: purity, sin, redemption.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For convincing disagreement with the notion that the steps actually represent not the \softline
process of the Sacrament of Penance but three stages in the sinner's contrition see Bosco/Reggio \softline
(comm. to verse 94).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 94-96.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The first step, of white marble, serves as a mirror to the protagonist and thus \softline
seems associated with confession.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 97-99.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The second, darker than the purple-black of the color perse and broken by a \softline
cruciform crack, represents the sinner's recognition of his 'broken' state.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 100-102.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The third, red with the color of spurting blood reminiscent of the sacrifice of \softline
Jesus Christ, is, like the first, of a stone of lofty character, porphyry (the second seems to be \softline
