}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab For hundreds of years Rome had kept a part of its treasure secure from any use, locked \softline
behind a portal that was never opened, until Caesar, in order to fund his pursuit of Pompey and \softline
Cato in 49 B.C., broke into the treasury and looted it, overcoming the resistance of a single brave \softline
republican, Metellus, loyal to Pompey.  Dante's source here is the violently republican Lucan \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Phars}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.108-168).  It is worth reading the entire passage, which most commentators apparently \softline
do not do, for it drips with sarcasm about Julius Caesar, from its inception, in which Caesar, \softline
having marched on Rome and conquered by arms, has become everything and the senate has \softline
become a mouthpiece for this 'private man,' to its conclusion, in which the city is portrayed as \softline
being poorer than the one man who rules her as a result of his plundering the temple of Saturn, \softline
her treasury.  There is nothing good here about Caesar, despite Dante's respect for him as the \softline
person he considered the first emperor of Rome (see Stull and Hollander, "The Lucanian Source \softline
of Dante's Ulysses," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studi Danteschi}{\plain \fs24 \f1  63 [1991 (1997)], pp. 33-43, for Dante's mainly negative, if \softline
mixed, views of Julius in the poem).  And thus the sound that sounds so shrilly at Dante's entrance \softline
into purgatory is reminiscent of what, for Lucan and for Dante, is perhaps the nadir of Roman \softline
history, the accession of Caesar and the destruction of the republic.  For Dante's fervent belief in \softline
the republican virtues and form of government see Hollander and Rossi ("Dante's Republican \softline
Treasury," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante Studies}{\plain \fs24 \f1  104 [1986], pp. 59-82).  Along with the passage in Lucan, undoubtedly \softline
Dante's main source here, Tommaseo (comm. to vv. 133-135) brings into play }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
VI.573-574: tum demum horrisono stridentes cardine sacrae / panduntur portae (then at last, \softline
grating on their hinges, the impious gates swing open).  Virgil is describing the gates of Tartarus, \softline
swinging open (the Sibyl and Aeneas do not enter, but she does tell him of the horrors of the \softline
punishments therein).  Here, too, we can see how Dante has juxtaposed two similar objects, the \softline
gates of Tartarus, the pagans' hell, and those of purgatory, and make the reader aware of the \softline
crucial similarity that marks their utter difference.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab What is the effect of such negative reminiscences as the protagonist begins to attain the \softline
Promised Land?  One must conclude that we are dealing here with antithesis: as brutally shrill as \softline
was the sound of the squealing doors of the temple of Saturn, of the gates of Tartarus, exactly so \softline
terribly loud is the rare victory of a penitent being allowed to enter the kingdom of Heaven -- or \softline
its vestibule.  What was tragic in its consequence for Rome is marked by a sound exactly as loud \softline
and grating as this one that announces the victory of a new (and better) Caesar who enters not \softline
against the will of the warder, but in accord with it.  Only the sounds are similar; all else is \softline
changed.  And, as we have seen occur several times in the first half of this canto, tragic classical \softline
myth or history gives way to comic Christian narrative.  In the words of Jesus (Luke 12:34), 
'There where your treasure is, there your heart is also.'  Caesar's treasure is far different from the \softline
treasure in Heaven sought and found by only relatively few Christians, their low numbers \softline
suggested by the infrequent screechings of this gate.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab As for the positive resolution for the unpleasant sound of the opening gate, Denise \softline
Heilbronn ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Concentus musicus}{\plain \fs24 \f1 : The Creaking Hinges of Dante's Gate of Purgatory," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Rivista di \softline
studi italiani}{\plain \fs24 \f1  2 [1984], pp. 1-15) points out that medieval concepts of musical 'sweetness' had \softline
more to do with harmony than with the sounds themselves.  She (p. 4) gives the examples of the \softline
hurdy-gurdy and drum, both of which would hardly seem to be 'sweet' to modern ears, but did to \softline
those of the time who recorded their responses.  This point is a pivotal one for those who cannot \softline
bring themselves to see how the grating screech of a gate can be in harmony with another sound.  \softline
Yet when we reflect, along with Heilbronn, that what the gate's sound announces is very sweet \softline
indeed, we may begin to understand Dante's strategy here.  M.A. Buchanan ("At the Gate of \softline
Purgatory [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IX, 130-145, X, 1-6]," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Italica}{\plain \fs24 \f1  25 [1948], pp. 6-7) points out that there are three \softline
musical moments in the scene: the roaring of the hinges, the harmonious singing of the angels who \softline
are apparently within the gates, and the sound of the gate closing behind Dante in the fourth verse \softline
of the next canto.\par
